(34, 12, 2, 0, 2, 0, 'Page', '2017-10-27 12:16:59', '2017-10-27 12:14:00', 'frequently-asked-questions', 'Frequently Asked Questions', 'FAQ', '<p>How many photos should I upload?</p><p>Photos are very valuable for the tenderers pricing the work. Upload enough photos to clearly show all facets of the job, the surrounding environment, access points and sensitive areas (eg. your favourite tree which you don\'t want cut down).</p><p>Do I need to upload a sketch or plan?</p><p>This depends entirely on the job. A tender for a job to clean a building would normally not require a sketch or plan. A tender for a tree removal would be made clearer with a sketch showing where the cut branches are to be stacked. A tender for the construction of a shed would need a clear plan and a tender for the construction of a house would need several sheets of detailed design plans.</p><p>Should I upload a video?</p><p>This depends on the scale of the work. A video is valuable to communicate to the tenderers the scale of the project, describe some of the aspects of the project that are difficult to communicate in words and provide an idea of the surrounding environment.</p><p>Do I need to include contract documents when I set up the tender?</p><p>This depends on the level of complexity of the project and the value of the work. If the tender is to paint a fence then contract documents would be unlikely to be needed; the contract would be based on the detail provided in the description, the photos provided, the price and any other details provided in the Question and Answers. If the tender is to build a house then it would be usual to include a full package of documents with the tender, such as drawings, specifications, terms of payment, conditions.</p><p>What information do I need to provide when I submit my price?</p><p>This depends on what the purchaser requires. As a minimum you will need to submit a price only. Other information that may be required by the purchaser includes clarifications and notes, schedule of prices, sketches/designs and other documents as required by the purchaser. Note that when you submit the tender you will be required to confirm that you have read and understood all the information provided by the purchaser.</p><p>What if the price submitted differs from the schedule of prices (if submitted)?</p><p>The total price submitted takes precedence over the schedule of prices. The purchaser and seller will have to negotiate changes to the schedule of prices so that it matches the total price.</p><p>When I assess the tenders do I need to accept the lowest price?</p><p>You are bound to assess the tenders according to the conditions of tendering (if included in the tender documentation). If the tender is a simple one with no terms and conditions then you are to use your own judgement to assess which tender provides the best fit for the services you require.</p><p>What protection does Honest Day\'s Work offer buyers?</p><p>Honest Day\'s Work provides a service to connect buyers with sellers. It is up to the buyer and seller to agree on the terms of the contract, the price and the timeframe. Once the tender process is complete and the contract has been awarded Honest Day\'s Work involvement in the process is complete and the completion of the contract is then between the buyer and the seller.</p><p>What if circumstances out of my control, such as the weather, mean the contract is delayed?</p><p>Each scenario will be different; it is up to the parties to consider if the circumstances are covered in the conditions of contract (if part of the contract), or if not if the circumstances represent a fair and reasonable reason for delay. If the parties can not come to an agreement then the Small Claims tribunal is an option for resolution.</p><p>I want to ask a tender question that contains commercially sensitive information - should I do this.</p><p>You can ask commercially sensitive questions; if the purchaser thinks it is appropriate they will make the question and answer only viewable to you. If you are concerned that the information is highly sensitive then it is best not to disclose it.</p><p>What if you disagree with feedback that has been submitted against your account?</p><p>In the case of feedback being given which you disagree with Honest Day\'s work will assess the nature of the feedback provided by both parties and make a decision regarding weather the feedback is warranted or should be modified/removed. We undertake to make a fair and consistent decision on feedback; if either party remains unhappy we can review the facts and reconsider our decision. Where disagreement remains between the buyer and the seller it may be appropriate for the parties to take the dispute to the small claims tribunal.</p><p>What is the difference between and Open Tender and a Closed Tender?</p><p>An open tender is one that is visible to all users and for which tenders can be submitted by all users. A closed tender is one where the purchaser invites specific users to price the work. Invited tenders are suitable for work that is highly specialised and the interested sellers are well known, or for work where the purchasers experience/knowledge determines that the best value for money and quality is only provided through certain sellers. A closed tender will not appear on searches.</p><p>How do I pay for setting up or submitting a tender?</p><p>There are two options. PayPal accepts all major credit cards. POLI is a system where you can log into your bank with the Honest Day\'s Work environment and make a direct debit payment. Both of these systems are secure. We do not retain credit card details; the payments are handled entirely by PayPal and POLI.</p>', NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 11, 0, 0, NULL, 'Inherit', 'Inherit', 0),
