(85, 16, 10, 1, 2, 2, 'Page', '2017-11-10 13:52:45', '2017-11-10 13:32:44', 'reference-material', 'Reference Material', NULL, '<p>This material is provided to give guidance on common tendering practices in New Zealand. When preparing tender documentation it is important to understand the level of risk you are comfortable with. For example if you are setting up a tender for the construction of a fence, and you believe the cost is around $1,000, you may be comfortable with specifying all your requirements through photos, a sketch and a description of the work. If a dispute arose around some aspect of the work then this could be dealt with in the small claims tribunal and the cost at stake may be manageable.</p><p> </p><p>If the tender being set up was for the construction of a house then the level of risk would be significantly higher and it would be necessary to have drawings and tender documentation prepared to ensure both parties understood what was required, when payments would be made, what would happen if the work was delayed etc. The investment in time/cost to prepare the documents would be worthwhile considering the risk being managed.</p><p> </p><p>Below are templates and guidance on common aspects of tendering. If you are not sure if you need these documents or not it is always best to consult a professional.</p><p> </p><h2>Drawings/Sketches</h2><p>A simple job such as a fence may just require a sketch showing the location, length, height, foundations etc. Larger jobs will often require pages of detailed drawings showing precise measurements and critical features of the work.</p><p> </p><h2>Conditions of Tendering</h2><p>Conditions of Tendering describe the rules of the tendering and tender assessment process. This ensures that both Tenderers and the Client understand what information needs to be provided with the Tender and the process the Client will go through to assess and award the contract.</p><p> </p><h2>Standard Conditions</h2><p>Standard Conditions 