es that both Tenderers and the Client understand what information needs to be provided with the Tender and the process the Client will go through to assess and award the contract.</p><p> </p><h2>Standard Conditions</h2><p>Standard Conditions is a document which sets out the rules and method of managing a contract. Common standards used in New Zealand are:</p><p>· NZS 3910:2013 - Construction</p><p>· NZS 3916:2013 - Design and Construct</p><p>· NZS 3917:2013 - Fixed Term</p><p>Other standards are also available.</p><p> </p><h2>Special Conditions</h2><p>Special conditions modify the standard conditions so that the conditions better suit the needs/complexities of your own project.</p><p> </p><h2>Estimate</h2><p>For some jobs, particularly large and complex work, it is helpful to provide an estimate for the Tenderers. Normally this is prepared by an Engineer or someone who has a good understanding of the work. This will help the Tenderers quickly gauge the scope of the work and your expectations around the cost.</p><p>The estimate should include GST.</p><p> </p><h2>Schedule of Prices</h2><p>A schedule of prices is a breakdown of the price structure line by line. It provides the Tenderers with a format for breaking down their price which makes it easy to compare particular items between Tenders submitted. Once the job is awarded the schedule then provides a means of recording and claiming costs as the work is progressively completed. Essential for complex jobs.</p><p> </p><h2>Terms/Basis of Payment</h2><p>Terms of Payment (or Basis of Payment), describes how and when payments will be made. This is important for work which may span several months, is high risk or has more than one or two elements. Usually the Terms of Payment will refer directly to the schedule of prices and describe how each line item will be paid.</p><p> </p><h2>Specification</h2><p>A specification is a written document which describes the requirements of the work. This could be a short document for simple work or a larger document for more complex work. Normally it would contain sections which align with the schedule of prices and the drawings. Often the specification will refer to well known standards, ensuring the work is completed to best practice. Essential for complex work.</p><p> </p><h2>Extra Reading</h2><p>The New Zealand government have rules for government agency procurement and tendering. While these may be a lot to read through and more onerous than what is required for your job, they do contain some good principals that will help you understand the process. These are:</p><p><a title=\"The Five Principals of Government Procurement\" href=\"http://www.procurement.govt.nz/procurement/pdf-library/agencies/rules-of-sourcing/five-principles-of-government-procurement.PDF\" target=\"_blank\">The Five Principles of Government Procurement</a></p><p><a title=\"Government Rules of Sourcing\" href=\"http://www.procurement.govt.nz/procurement/pdf-library/agencies/rules-of-sourcing/procurement-government-rules-of-sourcing-v3.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Government Rules of Sourcing</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>', NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 15, 0, 0, NULL, 'Inherit', 'Inherit', 0);
