(107, 12, 13, 1, 2, 2, 'Page', '2017-11-10 15:25:07', '2017-10-27 12:14:00', 'frequently-asked-questions', 'Frequently Asked Questions', 'FAQ', '<h3>How many photos should I upload?</h3><p>Photos are valuable for the tenderers pricing the work. Upload enough photos to clearly show all facets of the job, the surrounding environment, access points and sensitive areas (eg. your favourite tree which you don\'t want cut down). Note that we limit the size of the photos to a maximum of 2Mb each; you may need to lower the resolution of your camera to ensure the photos are below this limit.</p><p> </p><h3>Do I need to upload a sketch or plan?</h3><p>This depends entirely on the job. A tender for a job to clean a building would normally not require a sketch or plan. A tender for a tree removal would be made clearer with a sketch showing where the cut branches are to be stacked. A tender for the construction of a shed would need a clear plan and a tender for the construction of a house would need several sheets of detailed design plans.</p><p> </p><h3>Should I upload a video?</h3><p>This depends on the scale of the work. A video is valuable to communicate to the tenderers the scale of the project, describe some of the aspects of the project that are difficult to communicate in words and provide an idea of the surrounding environment. Ensure video file sizes are kept to a minimum to assist with upload and download speeds.</p><p> </p><h3>Do I need to include contract documents when I set up the tender?</h3><p>This depends on the level of complexity of the project and the value of the work. If the tender is to paint a fence then contract documents would be unlikely to be needed; the contract would be based on the detail provided in the description, the photos provided, the price and any other details provided in the Question and Answers. If the tender is to build a house then it would be usual to include a full package of documents with the tender, such as drawings, specification