ender is a simple one with no terms and conditions then you are to use your own judgement to assess which tender provides the best fit for the services you require. If the tender is more complex, with conditions of tendering as part of the tender docmentation, you are bound to assess the tenders according to the conditions of tendering.</p><p> </p><h3>What protection does Honest Day\'s Work offer buyers?</h3><p>Honest Day\'s Work provides a service to connect buyers with sellers. The buyer and seller to agree on the terms of the contract, the price and the timeframe. When the tender process is complete and the contract has been awarded Honest Day\'s Work involvement in the process is complete and the completion of the contract is then between the buyer and the seller.</p><p> </p><h3>What if circumstances out of my control, such as the weather, mean the contract is delayed?</h3><p>Each scenario will be different; it is up to the parties to consider if the circumstances are covered in the conditions of contract (if part of the contract), or if not if the circumstances represent a fair and reasonable reason for delay. If the parties can not come to an agreement then the Small Claims tribunal is an option for resolution.</p><p> </p><h3>I want to ask a tender question that contains commercially sensitive information - should I do this.</h3><p>You can ask commercially sensitive questions; if the purchaser thinks it is appropriate they will make the question and answer only viewable to you. If you are concerned that the information is highly sensitive then it is best not to disclose it.</p><p> </p><h3>What if you disagree with feedback that has been submitted against your account?</h3><p>In the case of feedback being given which you disagree with Honest Day\'s work will assess the nature of the feedback provided by both parties and make a decision regarding weather the feedback is warranted or should be modified/removed. We undertake to make a fair and consistent decision on feedback; if either party remains unhappy we can review the facts and reconsider our decision. Where disagreement remains between the buyer and the seller it may be appropriate for the parties to take the dispute to the small claims tribunal.</p><p> </p><h3>What is the difference between and Open Tender and a Closed Tender?</h3><p>An open tender is one that is visible to all users and for which tenders can be submitted by all users. A closed tender is one where the purchaser invites specific users to price the work. Invited tenders are suitable for work that is highly specialised and the potential tenderers are well known, or for work where the purchasers experience/knowledge determines that the best value for money and quality is only provided through certain tenderers. A closed tender will not appear on searches.</p><p> </p><h3>How do I pay for setting up or submitting a tender?</h3><p>There are two options. PayPal accepts all major credit cards. POLI is a system where you can log into your bank with the Honest Day\'s Work environment and make a direct debit payment. Both of these systems are secure. We do not retain credit card details; the payments are handled entirely by PayPal and POLI. POLI supports direct debits with the following banks ANZ, ASB, BankDirect, Bank of New Zealand, Kiwibank, TSB Bank and Westpac and is used by other large organisations such as NZTA, Bunnings and the Wharehouse. More information on POLI and PayPal can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a title=\"PayPal\" href=\"https://www.paypal.com/nz/home\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"leftAlone\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" title=\"\" src=\"assets/Uploads/_resampled/ResizedImageWzE5OCw3OF0/Paypal.JPG\" alt=\"Paypal\" width=\"198\" height=\"78\"></a></p><p>  <a title=\"POLI\" href=\"https://www.polipay.co.nz/\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"leftAlone\" style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" title=\"\" src=\"assets/Uploads/_resampled/ResizedImageWzE5OSw4MV0/POLI.JPG\" alt=\"POLI\" width=\"199\" height=\"81\"></a></p><h3>I\'m still not sure...</h3><p>Read the information on our resources pages:</p><p><a title=\"Resources for Preparing Tenders\" href=\"[sitetree_link,id=16]\">Resources for Preparing Tenders</a></p><p><a title=\"Resources for Submitting Tenders\" href=\"[sitetree_link,id=17]\">Resources for Submitting Tenders</a></p><p> </p>', NULL, NULL, 1, 1, 13, 0, 0, NULL, 'Inherit', 'Inherit', 2);
